icontrol.drivers

Class GenericGPIB

  • java.lang.Object
    • icontrol.drivers.Device
      • icontrol.drivers.GenericGPIB

  • @iC_Annotation(CommPorts=GPIB)
public class GenericGPIB
extends Device
    Generic GPIB Instruments are registered in Dispatcher.RegisterDeviceClasses with this class as their Instrument-Class. Essentially all functionality to support generic GPIB Instruments is implemented in class Device, hence, this class only overrides the getInstrumentNameIdentifier method, because Instrument-Name-Identifiers are not supported by generic GPIB Instruments, and also Open because generic GPIB instruments are assumed to be non IEEE 488.2 compliant (no *CLS is sent upon open).
    Version:
    0.1
    Author:
    KPP (Kurt Pernstich: pernstich@alumni.ethz.ch)

    • Method Detail

      • getInstrumentNameIdentifier

        protected java.lang.String getInstrumentNameIdentifier()
        Overrides the standard getInstrumentNameIdentifier method which retrieves the Instrument Name Identifier (part of the response to a *IDN? query) from the iC.properties. Instead, the Instrument Name Identifier used to define the generic Instrument is returned.

        Note: At time of writing, the Instrument-Name-Identifier is not supported for generic Instruments, hence, this method always returns an empty String.

        Overrides:
        getInstrumentNameIdentifier in class Device
        Returns:
        The Instrument Name Identifier that was defined for the generic GPIB Instrument. Because generic Instruments do not support Instrument Name Identifiers, this String is always empty.

      • Open

        public void Open()
        See also Device.Open().

        This overridden method for generic GPIB instruments assumes that the instrument does NOT implement IEEE 488.2 common commands, hence, it does not send *CLS and it does not call checkIDN - it actually does nothing and just returns.

        A later implementation might define an extra command for generic GPIB instruments like "supports 488.2" which could then be used to check if a *CLS should be sent. An other possibility would be to define an extra command to define IDN and use a non-empty IDN to also send *CLS.

        To clear the event status and error queue, use the script-command Instrument-Name SendCommand *CLS

        Overrides:
        Open in class Device
